“Gone with the Wind”: Film legend Olivia de Havilland is dead
The film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland is dead.
She died of a natural birth on Sunday in Paris at the age of 104, her spokesperson said to the German Press Agency.
She was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the southern epic, “Gone with the Wind” (1939).
Born to British parents in Tokyo, Olivia de Havilland moved to California as a small child.
The Austrian theater personality Max Reinhard discovered the 19 year-old in the role of Hermia in Shakespeare’s “A Midsummer Night's Dream”.
Warner Brothers film studio took her immediately under a seven year contract and she made it big alongside Eroll Flynn.
She filmed eight films with the heart breaker.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar as the main role in “To Each His Own”.
The film premiered in Germany under the title “Mutterherz”.
Three years later she got the designation as best actress in William Wylers “The Heiress”.
She received much recognition as a neurotic eccentric in “The Dark Mirror” and “The Snake Pit”.
Daphne du Maurier suggested her for the main roll in her 1952 filming of her novel “My Cousin Rachel”.
This show was a worldwide success.
She played with her long-term friend Bette Davis in “Hush...Hush, Sweet Charlotte”.
Her son Benjamin was born out of her marriage with the writer Marcus Goodrich (1946 to 1953).
She married the journalist Pierre Paul Galante in Paris and had her daughter Gisèle with him.
This marriage also came to an end.
Rumors about an affair with British Prime Minister Edward Heath were never confirmed.
