“Young people should get their cars back unharmed in the end.”
Numbers from the employment agency: 900 cases of suspected abuse of short-term work
Berlin - The Federal Employment Agency (BA) is pursuing about 900 suspected cases of abuse of short-term work.
“Given the 888,000 companies who reported short-term work, that is an extremely small amount,” management board member for operations Daniel Terzenbach told the “Frankfurter Allgemeinen Zeitung”.
When many companies suddenly applied for short-term work at the beginning of the corona crises, the BA needed to react quickly.
Normally the review process lasts up to three week.
“We didn’t have that kind of time available to us in this critical phase.
That is why we will look even more closely at the final accounts.
There will certainly still be more to come.
We are not naive about that and we have endurance”.
The evidence of abuse often came from affected employees and unions.
The BA’s analytics software was then used to detect the patterns of abuse.
The BA is preparing for a likely wave of insolvencies in Autumn, according to Terzenbach.
“Will there be significantly more insolvencies then last year?
The estimates are diverging from one another, but we are arming ourselves for a worst-case scenario and are already training our employees in the employment agency to process applications for insolvency money”.
