Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green has died
His life was a roller coaster ride: Following a lighting-fast assent with Fleetwood Mac, he went into a steep fall and then came slowly back up again.
Now the blues rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Great guitarist, drug addict, cult member: The co-founder of Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members reported on Saturday in an official statement, a further statement was announced for the upcoming days.
Top musicians such as Peter Frampton consider Green to be one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
In an emotional reaction, Mick Fleetwood spoke of a “monumental loss“ for all previous and current members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
The drummer Fleetwood and the guitarist Green founded the now legendary band in London in 1967, his dreamy instrumental hit “Albatross” remains unforgettable up into the current day.
The life of the musician (“The End Of The Game”, “In The Skies”) was like a roller coaster ride.
Green experienced a lighting-fast rise as part of Fleetwood Mac, however, the band celebrated their greatest successes without him.
Among other factors, there were fights because Green wanted to donate the profits of the group to good causes.
He started to appear in wide robes and with a giant crucifix.
Mental-health issues also seemed to have played a role.
Green left in 1970 just three years after founding the band.
A social descent followed.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, as biographers report.
Green was treated in the psychiatric ward for a long time.
The musician disappeared from the scene for a large part of the 1970s.
He supposedly lived on the street for a time, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent sometime in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 as the son of a Jewish working-class family in the London borough of Bethnal.
In his younger years he was already excited about US blues musicians like B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
He learned his first guitar chords at eleven.
At 15 the teenager started to play professional guitar and got the chance five years later to stand on stage as the lead guitarist for the instrumental group Peter B’s Looners.
A little later he was working as the stand-in for his idol Eric Clapton with the Bluesbreakers.
In the middle of the Blues Boom, Green founded Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 together with his Bluesbreakers colleagues Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
“Albatross”, a song composed by Green, ensured the group their first No.1 hit in the winter of 1968/1969 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
The quick accent showed its dark side quickly: Green did not deal with the media circus well and his experiments with the drug LSD got progressively more extreme.
He commented later in an interview about his life between music and addiction: “The worst that happened to me in life was the drugs, the best was to land the no.1 hit”.
At the end of the decade, Green managed a surprising, respectable achievement in 1979 with an album inspired by religious themes.
Fleetwood Mac in the meantime floated on a wave of success in a new formation without him.
The 1977 album “Rumours“ sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
In spite of small solo successes, Green never managed a great comeback, until he started anew in 1996 with a group of musician friends.
The British “Daily Telegraph” spoke at the time from a rockstar come back from the grave.
Green released a few albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group before the band broke up in 2004.
He was already a blues legend for music experts during his lifetime, and an influential guitarist of past decades with his gentle sounds.
